    <para id="id45283099">The region of convergence is outside a circle of radius one called the unit circle.</para>
    <para id="id45283116">
      <media id="id1167625265060" alt=""><image src="../../media/graphics5-cafa.png" mime-type="image/png" height="206" width="255"/></media>
    </para>
    <para id="id45400011">On the unit circle, 
<m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mstyle fontsize="12pt"><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>z </m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext> e</m:mtext><m:mstyle fontsize="8pt"><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>j</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">Ω</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:msup></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mstyle><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"z "=" e" rSup { size 8{j %OMEGA } } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. As we shall see, the unit circle in the z-plane plays a role analogous to the jω-axis in the s-plane.</para>
    <para id="id45400116">3/ Causal exponential DT time function</para>
    <para id="id45400124">If 
<m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mstyle fontsize="12pt"><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext> a</m:mtext><m:mstyle fontsize="8pt"><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mi>u</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mstyle><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{x \[ n \]  =" a" rSup { size 8{n} } u \[ n \] } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> then the Z-transform is</para>
